{"parentUuid":"7d648192-81ac-4737-9701-282ff32d2cf8","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"97f8e502-2809-4fbe-ae25-bfe99bbaf354","agentId":"a056046afd74f4258","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Base directory for this skill: c:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\.claude\\skills\\ast-grep-rules\n\n<!-- loading: on-demand (invoked via the Skill tool when needed) — generated by scripts/list-skills.sh --annotate; do not hand-edit -->\n\n# ast-grep structural rules (project template)\n\n> **Project-scoped template.** Copy the rules you want into the project, adapt the\n> language/pattern, then commit. ast-grep is an **optional adjunct** to Semgrep/OSV/Trivy,\n> not a replacement — it shines at structural patterns that are awkward as regex.\n\n## When to use it\n\nInvoke `ast-grep` (CLI, `Bash(ast-grep:*)`) when a STRIDE efficacy question (U-02) or a\ndiff review needs a *syntax-shaped* check that a text regex would get wrong — e.g. \"is a\nCPU-hard call on the async event loop\", \"is this RLS policy created without FORCE\". It\nparses to an AST, so it does not false-match inside strings/comments the way `grep` does.\n\n## Advisory-only contract (hard boundary)\n\nast-grep findings go into **`security-report.md` prose only**. They **must NOT** feed any\n`security-status.json` count (`semgrep_findings`, `critical_count`, …) or any gate/loop-exit\nconjunct. Reason: unlike the wrapped scanners (U-09 stamps + `reconcile-scans.sh`\nrecomputes their counts from hash-verified artifacts), ast-grep has **no wrapper and no\ncount reconciliation yet**. Until it gets one (TA A-4 backlog), an ast-grep hit is a\n*lead to investigate*, never a number the gate trusts. If a hit reveals a real defect, the\nfix flows through the normal exploitable-finding path and shows up in the reconciled tools'\ncounts on the next scan.\n\n## Example rules (starter set — adapt per stack)\n\n### R1 — sync KDF / blocking call on the async event loop (Python)\nPairs with the async-runtime efficacy question. Flags a bcrypt/argon2/scrypt call made\ndirectly inside an `async def` (should be off-loaded to a thread pool).\n```yaml\nid: sync-kdf-in-async\nlanguage: python\nrule:\n  inside: { kind: function_definition, has: { field: async, regex: \"async\" } }\n  pattern: $HASHER.$METHOD($$$)\nconstraints:\n  HASHER: { regex: \"bcrypt|argon2|scrypt|pbkdf2\" }\nnote: CPU-hard KDF on the event loop blocks all concurrent requests — run it in a thread pool.\n```\n\n### R2 — RLS policy created without FORCE (SQL)\nPairs with the DB-privilege efficacy question. A table-owning role bypasses RLS unless the\ntable is `FORCE`d; a `CREATE POLICY` with no accompanying `FORCE ROW LEVEL SECURITY` is a\nlead to check ownership.\n```yaml\nid: rls-without-force\nlanguage: sql\nrule:\n  pattern: CREATE POLICY $$$\nnote: If the app role owns this table, RLS is advisory without ALTER TABLE ... FORCE ROW LEVEL SECURITY — verify ownership.\n```\n\n## Running\n\n```\nast-grep scan --rule <rule>.yml <path>      # one rule\nast-grep scan --config sgconfig.yml <path>  # a project rule set\n```\nRoute any raw output you keep to `.pipeline/` (never the tree/scratchpad), same as the\nother scanners. It does not need Docker — it is a single native binary.\n"}]},"isMeta":true,"uuid":"710c8a8d-6a00-4aa8-b20b-b4af48228966","timestamp":"2026-07-10T01:56:18.260Z","sourceToolUseID":"toolu_01M9jufNd75GVJ5nsAAy6Ag9","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"cb1e5971-0f87-4706-9a1d-09f830df9e6f","version":"2.1.205","gitBranch":"feature/quota-admin"}
